    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In "Not So Fast on the Ozone Layer Celebration" (letters, Sept. 14), Jeffrey Holman states, "two-thirds of all Australians are predicted to get skin cancer during their natural lifetimes because of ozone layer depletion."</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In "Not So Fast on the Ozone Layer Celebration" (letters, Sept. 14), Jeffrey Holman states, "two-thirds of all Australians are predicted to get skin cancer during their natural lifetimes because of ozone layer depletion."</p>
        <p>Regrettably, many Australians already have skin cancer due to sun exposure before ozone holes were ever heard of. The coming generation will be much less affected because of increased awareness and the liberal use of ultraviolet blockout lotions, developed in Australia over the last three decades.</p>
        <p>Many Australians are skeptical of the chlorofluorocarbon-ozone hole theory because more than 80 percent of chlorofluorocarbans are released in the Northern Hemisphere.</p>
        <p>So why is the hole in the Southern Hemisphere and not in the north? A more likely cause of the southern ozone hole is Mount Erebus, a huge active Antarctic volcano that regularly spews thousands of tons of chlorine vapor into the stratosphere.</p>
        <p>Yes, we must minimize the pollution of the atmosphere and the surface of the earth, but let's be guided by scientific common sense, not emotional half-truths. DAVID STEWART  Kenmore, Australia, Sept. 21, 1993</p>
      </block>
